Use the tidyr::uncount function to expand a frequency variable

lobster_tidy <- lobster_abundance %>% 
  uncount(lobster_count)

Yay! Now each lobster has its own row. This is tidy format.

Let’s look at this thing.

ggplot(data = lobster_tidy, aes (x = site, y = size_mm))+
  geom_jitter(aes(color = site),
              width = .2,
              alpha = .3)

Use lubridate to parse dates and times:

I’m going to add a new column with mutate() that contains my date as an actual date.

Parse ‘Date’ column to get the different piece (month, year) separated

lobster_parse_date <- lobster_date %>% 
  mutate(obs_month = lubridate::month(date_new, label = TRUE),
         obs_year = lubridate::year(date_new))

Count lobsters by different groupings…

Let’s say I wnt to count the number of lobsters by year and month

lobster_ym <- lobster_parse_date %>% 
  count(obs_year, obs_month)

lobster_ym

lobster_ysite <- lobster_parse_date %>% 
  count(obs_year, site)

lobster_site <- lobster_parse_date %>% 
  count(site)

lobster_summary <- lobster_parse_date %>% 
  group_by(site) %>% 
  summarize(
    mean_size = mean(size_mm, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_size = sd(size_mm, na.rm=TRUE),
    sample_n = n()
  )
  
lobster_summary

Confidence intervals and t-tests

Use the t-test() function to find confidence intervals and perform t-tests

ivee_lobsters <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == "IVEE") %>% 
  pull(size_mm)

t.test(ivee_lobsters)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  ivee_lobsters
## t = 245.23, df = 2302, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  72.99130 74.16806
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  73.57968

Two sample t-test: Is there a significant difference in mean lobster lengths between Naples Reef and Mohawk Reef?

napl_sample <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == "NAPL") %>% 
  pull(size_mm)

mohk_sample <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == "MOHK") %>% 
  pull(size_mm)

mohk_napl_ttest <- t.test(napl_sample, mohk_sample)
mohk_napl_ttest
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  napl_sample and mohk_sample
## t = 19.849, df = 1850.8, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  10.19806 12.43436
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  78.18454  66.86833

Mean lobster size differed significantly between Mohawk and Naples reefs. (t(1850.7720862) = 19.849)
